Do you agree to the theories of George Wald who said that life came from an electric

01:01:28.940 --> 01:01:34.500
strike like lightning that hit the elements, the earth's primordial atmosphere and life

01:01:34.500 --> 01:01:35.500
evolved from that.

01:01:35.500 --> 01:01:39.900
There was experiments where amino acids evolved into proteins in life form.

01:01:39.900 --> 01:01:42.940
Do you agree with those theories?

01:01:42.940 --> 01:01:51.500
I would not repeat them in the way their original investigators believed them to be true.

01:01:51.500 --> 01:01:54.340
Again to speak a little bit carefully.

01:01:54.340 --> 01:01:57.420
Lightning strikes turn out to matter on earth because they do something very difficult.

01:01:57.420 --> 01:02:02.700
They take N2 which is a very strong molecule and they break it up into the forms of nitrogen

01:02:02.700 --> 01:02:05.660
that wind up being chemically interesting.

01:02:05.660 --> 01:02:11.740
That may matter but I think it only matters at the scale of the whole planetary dynamic.

01:02:11.740 --> 01:02:15.740
The chemistry of the atmosphere is extremely different from the chemistry of life.

01:02:15.740 --> 01:02:18.740
You remember I said that chemistry in water is very restrictive and there are a lot of

01:02:18.740 --> 01:02:21.140
things that you can't do with it.

01:02:21.140 --> 01:02:27.300
The chemistry of carbon and of metals in the deep subsurface is incredibly similar to our

01:02:27.300 --> 01:02:28.780
biochemistry.

01:02:28.780 --> 01:02:33.380
So much so that you can look at enzymes that use metals and they use them as if they had

01:02:33.380 --> 01:02:38.260
just taken a mineral center and learned how to harness it for certain types of jobs.

01:02:38.300 --> 01:02:42.580
Those things were not known when George Wald was writing these things and I think a lot

01:02:42.580 --> 01:02:46.500
of the opinions you're talking about come more from Stanley Miller and the followers

01:02:46.500 --> 01:02:50.900
of Stanley Miller after 1953.

01:02:50.900 --> 01:02:54.900
His experiments were groundbreaking but there are two things, two ways you can interpret

01:02:54.900 --> 01:02:55.900
them.

01:02:55.900 --> 01:02:59.860
One you could suppose that those experiments were good models for the origin of life.

01:02:59.860 --> 01:03:03.940
That I think doesn't hold up so well now though there are still many people who would disagree

01:03:03.940 --> 01:03:05.420
with me.

01:03:05.420 --> 01:03:09.900
But what you could say instead is if chemistry in the atmosphere that's so different from

01:03:09.900 --> 01:03:16.420
biochemistry led to amino acids many of which are the same as those in biochemistry what

01:03:16.420 --> 01:03:22.100
should we be learning about the paths of least resistance in organic chemistry that can cause

01:03:22.100 --> 01:03:27.260
very different starting points to collapse into a few paths and then kind of like trees

01:03:27.260 --> 01:03:29.820
growing along the waterways in the desert.

01:03:29.820 --> 01:03:34.660
Does biochemistry use the chemicals it does because it's following those paths of least

01:03:34.660 --> 01:03:41.140
resistance even if we learned about them in the wrong environment?

01:03:41.140 --> 01:03:43.780
And there's somebody who really wants to ask another question and I don't want to cut

01:03:43.780 --> 01:03:44.780
them off.

01:03:44.780 --> 01:03:48.180
Okay, so you will be the last one.

01:03:48.180 --> 01:03:51.180
You've had your hand up three or four times.

01:03:51.180 --> 01:04:00.260
No, I'm almost embarrassed to stand up considering the quality of all the questions here but as

01:04:00.260 --> 01:04:05.180
a practical matter we are so familiar with the term climate change and what's happening

01:04:05.180 --> 01:04:07.420
in climate change.

01:04:07.420 --> 01:04:13.160
Is mankind doing anything relative to climate change that would affect your theories in

01:04:13.160 --> 01:04:19.020
any way shape or form or is they two completely different subjects?

01:04:19.020 --> 01:04:24.100
I'm so glad that you got a chance to ask because it would have been a shame not to hear.

01:04:24.100 --> 01:04:29.740
I don't think that the things that people are doing affect the theories but I would

01:04:29.740 --> 01:04:34.660
like this work to affect the things that people do.

01:04:34.660 --> 01:04:37.660
So this was the point that Jerry opened with.

01:04:37.660 --> 01:04:43.380
In biology too much we have put ecosystem sensibility kind of in the periphery and we

01:04:43.380 --> 01:04:49.220
focused on organisms and when we interact with a natural world whether we do it industrially

01:04:49.220 --> 01:04:54.900
or agronomically we try to engineer organisms and we try to influence systems with a few

01:04:54.900 --> 01:05:00.780
components as if we were building a watch or a bridge and routinely it winds up putting

01:05:00.780 --> 01:05:06.900
us in places where we don't want to be or where we shouldn't want to be.

01:05:06.900 --> 01:05:17.020
If biology can anchor ecology more centrally and start to understand the regression of ecosystems

01:05:17.020 --> 01:05:22.420
towards certain patterns that it's very hard to pull them away from maybe biology can help

01:05:22.420 --> 01:05:27.460
us head off misunderstandings in the world of application and make us a little bit more

01:05:27.460 --> 01:05:32.620
intelligent or in some cases a little bit more precautionary about what we do.

01:05:32.620 --> 01:05:38.660
Biology as a science is sound but biology as a science is not always proactive enough

01:05:38.660 --> 01:05:41.620
to anticipate the mistakes people are going to make.

01:05:41.620 --> 01:05:47.180
A more ecological biology may prime us to be a little bit better at second guessing the

01:05:47.180 --> 01:05:49.620
things that can go wrong and trying to be careful ahead of time.

